msIdentifier.repository: Kislak Center for Special Collections, Rare Books and Manuscripts

msContents.summary: The third in a series of at least eight ledgers in which John Archer recorded patient notes, fees, and debts. The first seven pages are an index of patient names arranged alphabetically, after which the chronological entries of the ledger begin in 1775 and continue to 1783. The last 33 pages, beginning from the end, contain a text in Latin titled "Compendium Logicae," copied by Archer as a student in the 1760s.

supportDesc.extent: 151 leaves : 191 x 150 mm. bound to 198 x 160 mm

binding.p: Contemporary sheep (bookseller's notes), back cover detached, spine damaged, front cover cut off about 47 mm. from spine.

origin.p: Written in Harford County, Maryland, between 1775 and 1783, except for the Compendium Logicae at the back, which was probably copied in Baltimore in 1764.

history.provenance: Bequeathed by Archer to the Medical & Chirurgical Faculty of Maryland; stamp on front pastedown of the library of the Medical & Chirurgical Faculty of Maryland.
